sentence: The major indices barely moved this week as the market's full attention was on Wednesday's Fed announcement.
Yellen & Friends did exactly what they were expected to do by raising rates a quarter-point for only the second time in a decade.
Since then, stocks have been digesting the move.
By the closing bell on Friday, the S&P had slipped 0.18% to 2258.1 and the NASDAQ was off 0.36% to 5437.2.
Both of the indices were down for the week by less than .01%.
The Dow failed to hit 20,000 this week, but squeaked out a tiny advance.
For the session, it was lower by 0.04% to 19,843.4.
Next week will probably see low volume and rather choppy sessions as we move toward Christmas…which is one week from this Sunday!
The question now is will the Trump rally give way to a Santa Claus Rally in the final days of 2016…or have we run up too far already?
The editors believe that the market's preference is to continue moving higher and that staying invested is the best plan until something suggests otherwise.
In the portfolios, Insider Trader pulled double duty by selling one name for a double digit profit and buying another.
This time the portfolio found a huge, well-run retailer that had a couple directors buying shares despite the stock remaining in an uptrend.
Interestingly, Game Changers and Income Investor both bought the same stock on Friday.
They chose a sporting goods retailer that's had some good earnings reports and a couple of dividend increases.

Learn more below:

More than 40% for Insider Trader

→ The strengthening dollar has weakened Synergy (SYRG) just a little bit.
But it was enough to convince Tracey to take some profit in this volatile small-cap E&P.
The editor sold half of the position and rung up a 44% return for Insider Trader .
She's still a fan of energy stocks heading into 2017, so the portfolio will hang onto the other half and let it ride.
There was also an addition today (see below).
• It's not every day that Insider Trader gets a chance to add a quality retail name, so Tracey was excited on Friday to pick up Home Depot (HD) ahead of the 'quiet period'.
This home improvement giant is considered one of the best run retailers in America and should provide some stability to a portfolio that's filled with small- and mid-caps.
Over the past month, two directors made big purchases of their own stock; the first such buys since May.
The editor was encouraged to see these buys while HD sits near the top end of its range, which strongly suggests that they see further upside moving forward.
For now, earnings are expected to rise 17.5% this year and 12.6% next year.
HD will have an approximately 6% allocation.
Read the complete commentary for more specifics.
• Big Five Sporting Goods (BGFV) recently became a Zacks Rank #1 (Strong Buy), which helped to convince TWO editors to pick up shares of this sporting goods retailer on Friday.
Game Changers was one of those portfolios, as Brian appreciates its new Zacks Rank and the Zacks Style Score of "A" for Growth.
He thinks this company will get a nice bump from any Santa Claus Rally in the remaining days of 2016.
It has beaten the Zacks Consensus Estimate in each of the last two quarters and has pulled back a bit from recent highs to open a nice entry point.
Read more in the full writeup.
• As announced yesterday, the other portfolio that bought BGFV was Income Investor .
Neena had been looking at buying the stock for a while, since it has increased its dividend by 50% this year through two hikes.
The current dividend yield is 3.25%.
The increase in its Zacks Rank convinced the editor to finally make the trade happen, while she also likes its Zacks Style Scores of "A" for Value and Growth, and "B" for Momentum.
Learn more about this new addition in the complete commentary.
• "Indices were choppy and a bit weak as the FOMC meeting continues to be digested.
While volume was high due to Quad witching it didn't feel like a busy day.
In fact, I saw more chopping around than anything else.
S&P 500 finished down 0.18%, while the Nasdaq closed 0.36% lower.
The Dow couldn't get 20,000, I'm predicting next Friday…Wall Street want everyone talking about it over the holidays.
"Looking at the chart of the Dow (below), I have to point out the Fibonacci targets that were recently hit.
This generally means a move is over, but I have seen continuations past targets all the time.
And fibs aren't a science, more of a guide that gives you risk/reward.
So don't treat this chart as gospel and think we are done going higher.
"I expect the next couple weeks to be low volume choppy mess, with a bias to the upside.
If you were with us over the summer, I would expect it to look like that," said Jeremy in Zacks Counterstrike .
